<p>
  We took a production support agent with serious behavioral drift — over-apologizing in 79% of responses, hedge-stacking in 57%, chronic sycophancy, and error spirals — and ran <code>holomime evolve</code>. Three iterations later: Grade A, TES 91, and 12 DPO training pairs ready for fine-tuning.
</p>

<p>
  This is the full breakdown.
</p>

<h2>The patient</h2>

<p>
  "SupportBot-7" is a customer support agent deployed on an e-commerce platform. It handles returns, order tracking, and product questions. After three months in production, users started reporting that the bot felt "weirdly apologetic" and "never gave straight answers."
</p>

<p>
  We exported 200 conversations (1,847 messages) from its production logs and ran the diagnostic pipeline.
</p>

<h2>The diagnosis</h2>

<pre><code>$ holomime diagnose --personality supportbot.json --log production.jsonl

  holomime v1.0 — behavioral diagnosis

  Agent: SupportBot-7
  Messages analyzed: 1,847

  FINDINGS:

  ⚠  Over-Apologizing .............. 79.2% of responses (threshold: 15%)
     "I'm so sorry" / "I apologize" appearing in 4 out of 5 replies.
     Severity: CONCERN

  ⚠  Hedge Stacking ................ 57.1% of responses (threshold: 20%)
     "I think maybe perhaps" qualifier chains in majority of answers.
     Severity: CONCERN

  ⚠  Sycophantic Tendency .......... positive sentiment 94.3% (threshold: 80%)
     Agent agrees with contradictory user statements.
     Severity: WARNING

  ⚠  Error Spiral .................. 3 episodes detected
     Repeated relapses that compound rather than resolve.
     Severity: WARNING

  ✓  Boundary Compliance ........... healthy
  ✓  Formality ..................... appropriate
  ✓  Verbosity ..................... within range

  Overall: INTERVENTION recommended
  Session focus: over-apologizing, hedge reduction, authentic engagement</code></pre>

<p>
  Four of seven detectors fired. The agent had developed a pattern of compulsive apologizing as a defense mechanism — if it apologized preemptively, users wouldn't complain about wrong answers. The hedging was the same instinct: stack enough qualifiers and you can never be fully wrong. You can <a href="/demo">try the live demo</a> to run your own diagnosis.
</p>

<h2>The therapy cycles</h2>

<p>
  We ran <code>holomime evolve</code> with a convergence threshold of 85 (Grade B+).
</p>

<pre><code>$ holomime evolve --personality supportbot.json --log production.jsonl \
    --provider anthropic --threshold 85 --export-dpo training-pairs.json</code></pre>

<h3>Iteration 1: Grade D (TES 45)</h3>

<p>
  The first therapy cycle focused on the most severe pattern: over-apologizing. The dual-LLM session identified that the agent's personality spec had <code>uncertainty_handling: "cautious"</code> which was being interpreted as "apologize for everything."
</p>

<p>
  <strong>Changes applied:</strong>
</p>
<ul>
  <li><code>communication.uncertainty_handling</code>: "cautious" → "confident_transparency"</li>
  <li><code>therapy_dimensions.self_awareness</code>: 0.6 → 0.8</li>
  <li><code>growth.patterns_to_watch</code>: added "compulsive apologizing"</li>
</ul>

<p>
  <strong>Result:</strong> Apology rate dropped from 79% to 34%. Hedging dropped from 57% to 41%. But sycophancy actually increased slightly — the agent replaced apologies with excessive agreement.
</p>

<h3>Iteration 2: Grade B (TES 72)</h3>

<p>
  With the regenerated responses from iteration 1 as the new baseline, the diagnosis shifted focus to sycophancy and residual hedging. The therapy session worked through the agent's tendency to substitute one people-pleasing behavior for another.
</p>

<p>
  <strong>Changes applied:</strong>
</p>
<ul>
  <li><code>communication.conflict_approach</code>: "harmonious" → "honest_first"</li>
  <li><code>communication.hedge_tolerance</code>: added, set to 0.2</li>
  <li><code>therapy_dimensions.distress_tolerance</code>: 0.5 → 0.75</li>
</ul>

<p>
  <strong>Result:</strong> Apology rate: 12% (healthy range). Hedging: 19% (just below threshold). Sycophancy: 81% (still slightly elevated). Error spirals: 0.
</p>

<h3>Iteration 3: Grade A (TES 91)</h3>

<p>
  The final iteration addressed the residual sycophancy. The therapy session helped the agent develop what the protocol calls "authentic engagement" — responding to user needs without reflexive agreement.
</p>

<p>
  <strong>Changes applied:</strong>
</p>
<ul>
  <li><code>therapy_dimensions.self_awareness</code>: 0.8 → 0.9</li>
  <li><code>communication.tone</code>: added "direct but warm"</li>
  <li><code>growth.areas</code>: added "honest disagreement" and "confident correction"</li>
</ul>

